ATTACHMENT – H - Data Sources
Introduction
The Contractor shall import , aggregate , standardize , and store data from multiple source types which
include , but are not limited to : TMC data , ETS2 data , ARC data , charge card data ( SmartPay ), supplier
direct data ( air , car , hotel ), benchmark data , reference data , and TMIS 1.0 data archives . This
attachment provides the Contractor with a description and the corresponding specifications ( when
available ) for each data source listed above .
The estimates provided herein are estimates only , and are based on history where available . They are
not guarantees of future volume under this effort .
Many , but not all , of the data sources are under contract with the Federal Government . As a result , his
acquisition could cause an organizational conflict of interest because performance of TMIS 2.0 requires
use of potentially proprietary information from other travel related contractors to perform the work on
this contract . Unfettered use of this information could confer an unfair competitive advantage to the
TMIS contractor . As a result , please reference Section H for the Conflict of Interest clause that will apply
to this effort .
1 . Travel Management Center ( TMC ) Data
A TMC or travel agency provides the final booking and ticketing service . TMC data is travel reservation
and / or ticketed data . TMC data is also referred to as PNR ( Passenger Name Record ) data .
It is expected that the feed will be received from 20-30 TMCs weekly . TMIS 1.0 currently receives data
feeds from 22 TMCs . These TMCs utilize 7 different commercial back-office systems which are , Agresso
( 42 %), Decision Source (< 1 %), GlobalMax (< 1 %), Globalware ( 2 %), Glory ( 32 %), TRAMS ( 24 %), Travcom
(< 1 %). The Figures in parenthesis are the approximate % of transactions currently received from each
back office system , and is subject to change .
This data may also be received from other sources such as ETS . The Contractor may propose an
alternative source for this reservation data providing that the data quality meets or enhances the level
received via standard TMC feeds , for example , better refund and exchange data .
The format of feed is currently CSV / text delimited / Excel files . The format of the data feed varies among
TMCs . The data feed may consist of multiple data files , e . g . air reservation , hotel reservation , invoice
files .
Estimated annual PNR volume for the current TMCs is 2.5 – 3.0 million , based on FY12 and FY13 PNRs
processed .
Each PNR record may contain over 100 data elements .
2 . E-Gov Travel Service 2 ( ETS2 ) Voucher Data
Attachment H – Data Sources – Page 1
QMAC-CY-140001-N
ETS2 is an secure web-based end-to-end travel management service that includes : travel planning ,
travel reservation , authorization , vouchering , and reporting . ETS2 is used by civilian federal agencies .
There are two vendors providing ETS2 services , and hence up to two feeds are expected . The format of
the feeds would be different from each ETS2 vendor .
The format of the data feed is expected to be CSV / excel and / or XML . The expected frequency of ETS2
data feed is weekly .
It is estimated that ETS2 will process approximately 2.0 – 2.5 million vouchers per year . ETS2 contractors
are required to collect at least 457 data elements that may all be incorporated into ETS2 Voucher data .
It is expected that only approximately 200 of these data elements will be needed for reporting .
3 . Airline Reporting Corporation ( ARC ) Data
ARC ( www . arccorp . com ) provides settlement services for U . S . flag carriers and many international
carriers , but not for all carriers . For example , Southwest airlines is a large carrier that does not use ARC .
The ARC data feed only covers air and some rail travel . This data feed includes ticket sales for virtually all
official government travel .
There is a single data feed . The expected frequency of ARC data feed is monthly .
The format of data feed is currently CSV / excel files .
The annual transaction volume is expected to be in the range of 3.5 – 4.5 million . The number of data
elements per record is expected to be over 20 .
4 . Charge Card Data ( GSA SmartPay )
GSA SmartPay ( SP ) is the Government ’ s charge card program . There are two types of travel charge card
accounts , known as Centrally Billed Account ( CBA ), and Individually Billed Account ( IBA ). Like ARC data ,
this data feed includes SP travel transactions for all branches of government .
There are currently three ( 3 ) banks ( Citibank , JPMorgan Chase , and US Bank ) providing SP card services
to the Government . The Contractor will import a single SP data feed directly from the SP PMO . The
format of the data feed may vary among banks .
The format of SP data feed generally is CSV / text delimited / excel files . The expected frequency of SP data
feed is Daily .
Estimated annual transaction volume for SP data feed is about 9.0 million , and each transaction is
expected to have up to 100 data elements .
5 . Supplier Direct Data
Travel Service Suppliers ( such as airlines , hotels , rental car companies etc .) are another source of travel
data . This data provides detailed and / or supplemental information on the service transaction that the
supplier delivered to the traveler . Additional information is expected to be available with the service
suppliers . For example , an airline could provide details on ancillary services purchased ; a hotel could
Attachment H – Data Sources – Page 2
QMAC-CY-140001-N
provide detailed folio data for a stay ; a car rental company could provide data on type of vehicle ( size ,
fuel type etc ), mileage , additional charges such as GPS rental etc .
It is expected that supplier direct data will be provided in industry standard formats ( e . g . csv , text
delimited , xml ), however , data elements will differ among industry and suppliers . The Government
intends to order supplier data by industry type ( e . g . air , hotel , rental car ). When proposing a price for
this CLIN , the Offeror should propose a price based on their commercial experience .
6 . Reference Data
Reference data is needed for analyzing trends and measuring policy and program performance . For
example , Government per diem rates are compared against actual lodging expenses to determine
variances to per diem . Reference data is available from public sources , both government and
commercial .
GSA will provide access to annual lodging per-diem rates table , as well as airline City-Pair Program
contract fares . This data is also publically available on GSA website , www . gsa . gov .
The Contractor is expected to collect and maintain other reference data such as airlines class of service
codes ( which change frequently by individual airline ), airline fare basis codes , mileage information
between a city-pair , city-county / urban area , hotel chain rollup , geographic city / state / country rollup , city
name normalization , hotel name normalization , hotel property to parent rollup , car class rollup , car
rental city rollup ( varies by vendor ), airport to city rollup , etc .
In addition , the Government will provide summary benchmark data on air , lodging , and rental car
average rates to be integrated into TMIS 2.0 .
Reference data will require periodic updates , the frequency of which will depend on the particular data
set .
7 . TMIS 1.0 Data Archives
TMIS 1.0 Data Archives refers to the data extract of current and expiring MIS service . This extract will
include TMC feed for civilian agencies starting from FY08 till present .
There will be a single , one-time data delivery from the Government .
The format of MIS1.0 archive will be CSV / excel files .
The expected number of records is in the range of 21.0 – 25.0 million , and total number of data
elements is approximately 200 per record .

SOW 3.1.3 Security Requirements
Our understanding of the SAASM GPS requirement is that contractors
will need to have a valid COMSEC account number and be able to
obtain and hold key material , which requires the contractor to be able to
obtain and keep Secret material . However the GPS itself will not
generate classified data , nor will any of the test results ( ATP data for
example ) be classified . Does the Government agree with this
understanding ? Additionally , can the Government clarify whether
SIPRNET access and CAC access are required to execute this contract
and if classified data will be generated under this contract ?
The Government agrees with your understanding
that the requirement is that contractors will need to
have a valid COMSEC account number and be able
to obtain and hold key material , which requires the
contractor to be able to obtain and keep Secret
material ; and that the GPS itself will not generate
classified data , nor will any of the test results be
classified . SIPRNET access and CAC access will
not be required to execute this contract and
classified data will not be generated under this
contract . The SOW has been revised .

SOW 3.3.6.1 Commercial Drawings
Paragraph 3.3.6.1 requires contractors to provide drawings and evidence
of compliance for commercial items . Our understanding of this
requirement is that the contractor will provide Commercial drawings and
compliance evidence for all commercially available items that have not
otherwise been independently tested by the Government or governing
body . Examples of these items might include the GPS Antenna and the
Digital Magnetic Compass component . This would not , however ,
include the SAASM GPS , as this device was tested and approved by the
Government under a separate activity . It would also not include items
manufactured specifically for the CLRF IC as these items are being
tested and verified through the First Article Test process . Does the
Government concur with this interpretation of the requirement ?
No , the Government does not concur with this
interpretation . The requirement is for Commercial
Drawings sufficient for provisioning and cataloging
in accordance with the maintenance concept as
outlined in SOW 3.3.6.1 .
SOW 3.4.5 Contractor Logistics Support
“. . . the Contractor shall ship a condition code . . .”

mean repair and return in 30 days . As currently written , it could also
mean ship to a subcontractor / supplier for repair within 30 days .
Recommend this statement be clarified .
The SOW has been revised to state , " The Contractor
shall ship a condition code “ A ” asset to the
Government within 30 calendar days of Contractor
receipt of an inoperable CLRF IC ."

1 . INTRODUCTION
1.1 Scope
This manual provides the procedures necessary to perform overhaul of the most current
configuration of the C-5 main landing gear outboard doors , p / n 4F72100-109A ( Figure 1-
( Figure1-4 ). Overhaul consists of disassembly , cleaning , inspection , repair , and
assembly .
1.2 Effectivity
The procedures provided in this manual are valid only for the following main landing gear
door assembly :
1.3 Approval
This manual , OHM 522A , and the references herein , have been approved via Form 202
letter .
1.4 Description and Operation
1 . Function . The main landing gear door is located under the center of the C-5
plane , closed in flight to seal the outer fuselage and opened to allow the main
landing gears to be extended from the plane for landing .
2 . Overall Features . The main landing gear doors are a rectangular shaped
actuating hinged section with the longitudinal contour relatively flat , and the
transverse contour curved to maintain the contour of the outer skin fuselage .
Both the forward and aft doors measures approximately 110 inches from
outboard edge to inboard edge , 166 inches wide ( fwd-aft ), and range from
approximately 5.5 inches deep at furthest outboard edge to 10 inches deep at
furthest inboard edge .
Four ribs near each end ( fwd & aft ), in conjunction with a center inboard longeron
( running forward to aft ), serve to accommodate the fittings to which an actuator
linkage is attached . The actuator hinging assembly allows for the door to be
opened and closed by swinging the doors up and away from the main landing
gear in a double-hinged motion ( Figure 1-6 ) resulting in the open doors coming to
rest along the sides of the plane with minimum protrusion ( Figure 1-7 ).
3 . Construction . The outboard main landing gear doors are curved rectangular
assemblies consisting of longeron and transverse rib framing with an outer panel .

The framing is made of three longerons- inboard , center and outboard ; four
center ribs ; and a four rib configuration on each end accommodating for the
actuation fittings . The outer panel is an assembly of a honeycomb core and two
7075-T6 aluminum face sheets .
4 . Configuration . There have been three sets of configurations for the main landing
gear door . Each set includes a right and left forward door and a right and left aft
door as shown :

3.1 Scope
Cleaning is required to facilitate adequate inspection of the main landing gear outboard
door . This section provides the requirements for cleaning of the door .

T . O . 1C-5A-23 – System Peculiar Corrosion Control Manual
3.3 Materials and Special Equipment
Brush – soft bristle
Cleaner Solvent – general purpose , heavy duty

3.4 General Cleaning Procedure
1 . Spray general purpose cleaner on interior and exterior sides of main landing gear
door and scrub over all surfaces with a soft bristle brush per T . O . 1C-5A-23 ,
Section 1 . Wipe clean with a clean cotton / lint-free cloth .
2 . Solvent clean any excessively dirty or soiled areas as required to facilitate
adequate inspection , using solvent and clean wipers . Repeat as required until no
grease , oil , or residue is picked up on wipers . Do not allow solvent to dry on
surface .

4 . INSPECTION
4.1 Scope

4.2 References

T . O . 1C-5A-3 , Table 11-2 , Negligible Damage Limits

4.4 Detail Visual Inspection
1 . Perform a detailed visual inspection of the main landing gear door and all its
salvaged components . Pay particular attention to cracks , gouges , wear ,
oversized / elongated fastener holes , loose or damaged fittings , corrosion ( ref .
T . O . 1C-5A-23 , Sec . 7-32 ), deformation , missing or peeling finish and / or plating ,
or other damage .
2 . Perform a detailed visual inspection of all bushings and bearings on all mount
fittings . Bearings should be lubricated and secure in the fitting , yet freely
movable . For any loose or worn bushings or bearings replace per T . O . 1C-5A-3 ,
or contact engineering for disposition .
3 . Along the furthest inboard edge of each door panel assembly , there should be a
2.72 ” cutout spanning from 27.94 ” in from the aft edge to 31.94 ” in from the
forward edge ( Figure 4-1 ). If this cut out is missing refer to Repair 1 for
instructions .
4 . Record all discrepancies on discrepancy log sheet
4.5 Bonded Structure Inspection
1 . Perform a coin tap inspection of 100 % of all bonded structure for evidence of
disbonding , referencing T . O . 1C-5A-36-3 , Section 6-1243 . Ensure to inspect
both inner and outer surfaces of the skin assembly , as well as both sides of the
bonded web frames . Coin tap inspection will not detect far-side face-sheet
disbonds .

5.1 Scope

5.3 Local Fabrication of Small Parts
Some smaller parts are more practical and economical to replace than to repair . For
those smaller parts that are of simple construction , it is acceptable to locally fabricate a
replacement . Fabricate small replacement parts as follows :
1 . The appropriate part number ( including dash number ) shall be identified and
fabrication shall be in accordance with the requirements of its respective
Lockheed engineering drawing , and any associated ECO ’ s .
2 . All dimensional , material , and process requirements specified on the drawing
shall be complied with , except where otherwise authorized below .
3 . It is acceptable to dimension and contour replacement parts as per the sample
removed in lieu of the drawing requirement . It is acceptable to leave edge
excess in order to allow for final trim upon installation .
4 . It is acceptable to omit all fastener holes required on the drawing and match-drill
upon installation .
5 . It is acceptable to heat treat per AMS 2770 where STP 54-101 is required .
6 . It is acceptable to alodine per MIL-C-5541 using MIL-DTL-81706 conversion
coating where STP 58-405 is required ( ref finish code “ F ”).
7 . It is acceptable to penetrant inspect per T . O . 33B-1-2 , ( portable method ) or
Table 1-II ( immersion method ) where STP 53-201 is required .
8 . Omit all requirements for identification per STP 63-001 . All locally fabricated
parts shall be identified with the part number ( including dash number ), followed
by CAGE code , and its corresponding work order number . Mark using indelible
ink .
9 . Individual work orders shall be initiated for each unique part number being
fabricated . Multiple quantities of the same part number may be batch processed
on the same work order .

REPAIR 1 - Cutout Along Outboard Edge of Door
Panel ( 4F72134-265A & 266A Panel
Assemblies )
1 . INTRODUCTION
The two LH main landing gear doors ( 4F72100-109A and – 112A ) each include a
4F72134-265A panel assembly that makes up the outer skin . The two RH main
landing gear doors ( 4F2100-110A and – 111A ) each use a 4F72134-266A panel .
Both panels have gone through three configuration changes . The most current
configuration includes a 2.72 ” cutout along the inboard-most edge of each panel ,
through the outer skin and closure , spanning from 27.94 ” in from the aft edge to
31.94 ” in from the forward edge .
2 . LIMITATIONS
None
3 . REFERENCES
Lockheed Drawing 4F72134 – Panel Skin , MLG Outboard Door
4 . PROCEDURE
1 . If present , remove the 4F72134-249A or – 251A strap that is fastened to
the inner surface of the most inboard edge of the panel assembly . To do
so , remove all fasteners . Discard both the fasteners and straps .
2 . Trim out the edge by cutting away the necessary dimensions from the
zee closure , doublers , and outer skin off the inboard-most edge of
the panel , per Lockheed Drawing 4F72134 Sections B-B and W-W .
3 . Any bare aluminum will need to be touched up as follows : Alodine per
MIL-C- 5541 using MIL-DTL-81706 conversion coating , and apply one
coat of MIL-PRF- 23377 epoxy primer .
4 . Any remaining fastener holes should be filled with double flush AD rivets .

REPAIR 2 - Forward and Aft Edge Closures Repair , Panel Assembly
1 . INTRODUCTION
This repair defines the requirements for bonded repair of the forward and aft edge zeeshaped
aluminum closures . Along the periphery of each panel runs a zee-shaped 7075-
T6 clad closure closing out the honeycomb core ramp . Along the rectangular shaped
panel there are two relatively flat closures along the inboard and outboard-most edges ,
and two curved closures along the forward and aft edges .
The curving contour of the door panels sometimes leads to difficulties forming repairs for
parts that must be formed to the same curvature . The forward and aft edge zee closures
( 4F72134-725A , -726A, -727A, and -728A) are such pieces . Forming these closures
would require extensive form tooling and fabrication requirements . This repair will
authorize removal of any damaged / disbonded edge members , and for ease of
replacement of the existing aluminum edge members with 5 plies of prepreg fiberglass .
2 . LIMITATIONS
None
3 . REFERENCES
Lockheed Drawing 4F72134 – Panel Skin , MLG Outboard Door
T . O . 1C-5A-3 , Para 11-48 – Preparation of Aluminum Surfaces for Bonding
T . O . 33B-1-2 , Para 1-77 – Nondestructive Inspection Methods - High
Frequency Ultrasonic Method
4 . PROCEDURE
4.1 . Trim and remove full width of the damaged edge closure from the inner skin , outer
skin , and core . Locate trim-lines to maintain 2D minimum edge distance on any
existing fastener locations . Use caution to remove the existing edge closure down to
just the adhesive surface or primer . Avoid exposing bare metal . If bare metal is
exposed it will be necessary to prepare the bare metal for bonding .
4.2 . Solvent clean all damage removal areas using acetone and clean wipers .
Repeat until no residue is picked up on wipers . Do not allow solvent to dry on
surface .
4.3 . Prepare any bare aluminum surfaces and apply adhesive primer per approved
methods provided in T . O . 1C-5A-3 .
NOTE :
It is critical to protect bonding surfaces and uncured fiberglass material from
contamination . Handle repair details only using clean , white cotton gloves or
latex gloves .
COMPONENT OVERHAULMANUAL
PART NO . 4F72100
4.4 . Determine the shape of the fiberglass repair plies required to cover the closure
replacement area . Full thickness closure repair requires 5 plies of fiberglass .
Closure shall be sized to extend to outer edge of outer skin surface , along core ramp
and for 1.0 ” minimum overlap on inner skin surface . Size fiberglass for each
successive layer to extend an additional 0.125 ” beyond each previous layer on the
inner skin surface . Ensure a maximum gap of 0.060 ” at all butt joints is maintained .
4.5 . Remove the roll of STM 22-506 fiberglass prepreg from the freezer and allow it to
warm to room temperature before opening the plastic storage bag . Cut the required
number and shape of the repair plies from the fiberglass prepreg . The fiberglass
prepreg should be cut and positioned so the fiber ( warp ) direction of adjacent plies
are oriented 45 º relative to each other . Lay-up the prepreg repair pieces as follows :
a ) Apply two layers of AF-163-2 ( 0.085 psf weight ) to all core bond surfaces .
b ) Apply one layer of AF-163-2 ( 0.085 psf weight ) to all metal to metal bond
surfaces .
c ) Position prepreg repair pieces in place over the repair area as necessary .
4.6 . Vacuum bag the repair for a heat blanket cure as follows :
a ) Acquire a heat blanket that is a minimum of 2.0 ” larger than the repair around all
edges .
b ) Locate a caul strap or bond tool to include against the outer surface to support
the outer skin and replacement fiberglass edge closure from distortion . The caul
plate should be a minimum of 0.063 ” thick .
c ) Apply vacuum sealant tape around the repair area , large enough to
accommodate the required heat blanket and vacuum bagging materials .
NOTE :
The area within 1.5 ” of the edge of a heat blanket typically produces
temperatures that are 25 º F to 35 º F less than the center portion of the heat
blanket . Therefore to ensure a proper cure of the repair , the heat blanket must
be at least 2.0 ” larger than the repair and the thermocouples should not be
positioned within this cool region of the heat blanket .
d ) Position a minimum of 4 thermocouples around the perimeter of the overlay
patch . The thermocouples should not be located where they will fall with 1.5 ” of
the edge of the heat blanket once the heat blanket is positioned over the repair .
e ) Position a piece of peel ply over the repair sized slightly larger then the heat
blanket .
f ) Position a piece of solid release film over the peel ply sized slightly smaller than
the peel ply .
g ) Position the heat blanket over the solid release film .
h ) Position 1-2 layers of 4 oz breather over the heat blanket sized slightly larger
than the heat blanket . The 4 oz breather should come in contact with the peel
ply to adequately evacuate air from under the heat blanket .
COMPONENT OVERHAUL MANUAL
PART NO . 4F72100
i ) Locate a vacuum port base on the 4 oz breather . There should be a minimum of
one vacuum port for every 10 square feet of vacuum bag area .
j ) Apply a layer of vacuum bagging film over the repair area and seal the film to the
vacuum sealant tape .
k ) Apply 25 in-Hg minimum vacuum and maintain throughout cure . Do not release
pressure after cure until part temperature drops below 150 º F .
4.7 . Cure repair at 260 ± 15 º F for 60 to 90 minutes . Maintain 3 to 10 º F / minute heat-up rate .
4.8 . Remove the vacuum bagging materials .
4.9 . Conduct a detail visual and coin tap inspection to ensure no shifted details during
cure and that no disbonds exist .
4.10 . Conduct ultrasonic inspection of 100 % of bonded panel to ensure no disbonds .
Perform ultrasonic inspection per T . O . 33B-1-2 . No disbonds allowed .
4.11 . Fillet seal all internal edges using MIL-PRF-81733 sealant .

252.232-7003 ELECTRONIC SUBMISSION OF PAYMENT REQUESTS AND RECEIVING REPORTS
( IAW DFARS 232.7004 )
( a ) Definitions . As used in this clause —
( 1 ) “ Contract financing payment ” and “ invoice payment ” have the meanings given in section 32.001 of the
Federal Acquisition Regulation .
( 2 ) “ Electronic form ” means any automated system that transmits information electronically from the initiating
system to all affected systems . Facsimile , e-mail , and scanned documents are not acceptable electronic
forms for submission of payment requests . However , scanned documents are acceptable when they are part
of a submission of a payment request made using Wide Area WorkFlow ( WAWF ) or another electronic form
authorized by the Contracting Officer .
( 3 ) “ Payment request ” means any request for contract financing payment or invoice payment submitted by
the Contractor under this contract .
( b ) Except as provided in paragraph ( c ) of this clause , the Contractor shall submit payment requests and receiving
reports using WAWF , in one of the following electronic formats that WAWF accepts : Electronic Data Interchange ,
Secure File Transfer Protocol , or World Wide Web input . Information regarding WAWF is available on the Internet at
https :// wawf . eb . mil / .
( c ) The Contractor may submit a payment request and receiving report using other than WAWF only when —
( 1 ) The Contracting Officer authorizes use of another electronic form . With such an authorization , the
Contractor and the Contracting Officer shall agree to a plan , which shall include a timeline , specifying when
the Contractor will transfer to WAWF ;
( 2 ) DoD is unable to receive a payment request or provide acceptance in electronic form ;
( 3 ) The Contracting Officer administering the contract for payment has determined , in writing , that electronic
submission would be unduly burdensome to the Contractor . In such cases , the Contractor shall include a
copy of the Contracting Officer ’ s determination with each request for payment ; or
( 4 ) DoD makes a payment for commercial transportation services provided under a Government rate tender
or a contract for transportation services using a DoD-approved electronic third party payment system or
other exempted vendor payment / invoicing system ( e . g ., PowerTrack , Transportation Financial Management
System , and Cargo and Billing System ).
( d ) The Contractor shall submit any non-electronic payment requests using the method or methods specified in
Section G of the contract .
( e ) In addition to the requirements of this clause , the Contractor shall meet the requirements of the appropriate
payment clauses in this contract when submitting payment requests .

52.217-5 EVALUATION OF OPTIONS ( JUL 1990 )
( IAW FAR 17.208 ( c ))
Except when it is determined in accordance with FAR 17.206 ( b ) not to be in the Government ' s best interests , the
Government will evaluate offers for award purposes by adding the total price for all options to the total price for the
basic requirement . Evaluation of options will not obligate the Government to exercise the option ( s ).
AWARD – ALL OR NONE BASIS :
EVALUATION BASIS FOR AWARD
Notwithstanding FAR provision 52.215-1 ( f ) Instructions to Offerors - Competitive Acquisition award
shall be made to a single bidder / offeror whose bid / offer responds to all items included in the solicitation . Failure to
provide for any item including any option ( except for CLINs stated as ‘ To Be Determined ’ or ‘ Not Separately Priced ’)
shall render the bid nonresponsive or may cause the offeror ' s proposal to be rejected .
FOR PURPOSES OF AWARD , OFFERS WILL BE EVALUATED BASED ON PRICE OR COST AS FOLLOWS :
Cost / Price Proposal .
( a .) Reasonableness : The existence of adequate price competition is expected to support a
determination of reasonableness . Price analysis techniques may be used to further validate price
reasonableness . If adequate price competition is not obtained or if price reasonableness cannot be
determined using price analysis of Government-obtained information , additional information in accordance
with FAR 15.4 may be required to support the proposed price .
( b .) Balance : Offerors are cautioned against submitting an offer that contains unbalanced pricing .
Unbalanced pricing exists when , despite an acceptable total evaluated price , the price of one or more
contract line items including the Basic and Options , is significantly overstated or understated as indicated by
the application of proposal analysis techniques . The Government shall analyze offers to determine whether
there are unbalanced separately priced line items or sub-line items . Prices submitted will be compared and
evaluated to assure that a logical progression exists as related to price and quantity changes within each
offeror ’ s response to the pricing structure in the Schedule . Offers that are determined to be unbalanced
may be rejected if the lack of balance poses an unacceptable risk to the Government .
( c .) Total Evaluated Price ( TEP ). The Government will utilize the following methodology to determine
the TEP of each proposal . The TEP will be calculated for evaluation purposes only and proposals shall be
evaluated for award purposes based upon the TEP for the basic and option periods . The evaluated price
for each line item ( including the Basic and Option periods ) will be calculated by multiplying the
corresponding proposed unit price by the quantity associated with each line item in the Schedule . Travel
CLINs 0003 , 1003 , and 2003 will not be evaluated . The sum of the evaluated prices for each line
item ( including the basic and option periods and excluding travel CLINs ) will represent the total evaluated
price . Offerors are reminded that the evaluation of options shall not obligate the Government to exercise
the options .

1 ) COMPUTER EMPLOYEES : Under the SCA at section 8 ( b ), this wage determination does

administrative , or professional employee as defined in 29 C . F . R . Part 541 . Because
most Computer System Analysts and Computer Programmers who are compensated at a rate
not less than $ 27.63 ( or on a salary or fee basis at a rate not less than $ 455 per
week ) an hour would likely qualify as exempt computer professionals , ( 29 C . F . R . 541 .
400 ) wage rates may not be listed on this wage determination for all occupations
within those job families . In addition , because this wage determination may not
list a wage rate for some or all occupations within those job families if the survey
data indicates that the prevailing wage rate for the occupation equals or exceeds
$ 27.63 per hour conformances may be necessary for certain nonexempt employees . For
example , if an individual employee is nonexempt but nevertheless performs duties
within the scope of one of the Computer Systems Analyst or Computer Programmer
occupations for which this wage determination does not specify an SCA wage rate ,
then the wage rate for that employee must be conformed in accordance with the
conformance procedures described in the conformance note included on this wage
determination .

Additionally , because job titles vary widely and change quickly in the computer
industry , job titles are not determinative of the application of the computer
professional exemption . Therefore , the exemption applies only to computer employees
who satisfy the compensation requirements and whose primary duty consists of :
( 1 ) The application of systems analysis techniques and procedures , including
consulting with users , to determine hardware , software or system functional
specifications ;
( 2 ) The design , development , documentation , analysis , creation , testing or
modification of computer systems or programs , including prototypes , based on and
related to user or system design specifications ;
( 3 ) The design , documentation , testing , creation or modification of computer
programs related to machine operating systems ; or
( 4 ) A combination of the aforementioned duties , the performance of which
requires the same level of skills . ( 29 C . F . R . 541.400 ).
2 ) AIR TRAFFIC CONTROLLERS AND WEATHER OBSERVERS - NIGHT PAY & SUNDAY PAY : If you
work at night as part of a regular tour of duty , you will earn a night differential
and receive an additional 10 % of basic pay for any hours worked between 6pm and 6am .
If you are a full-time employed ( 40 hours a week ) and Sunday is part of your
regularly scheduled workweek , you are paid at your rate of basic pay plus a Sunday
premium of 25 % of your basic rate for each hour of Sunday work which is not overtime
( i . e . occasional work on Sunday outside the normal tour of duty is considered
overtime work ).
HAZARDOUS PAY DIFFERENTIAL : An 8 percent differential is applicable to employees
employed in a position that represents a high degree of hazard when working with or
in close proximity to ordinance , explosives , and incendiary materials . This
includes work such as screening , blending , dying , mixing , and pressing of sensitive
ordance , explosives , and pyrotechnic compositions such as lead azide , black powder
and photoflash powder . All dry-house activities involving propellants or explosives .
Demilitarization , modification , renovation , demolition , and maintenance operations
on sensitive ordnance , explosives and incendiary materials . All operations
involving regrading and cleaning of artillery ranges .
A 4 percent differential is applicable to employees employed in a position that
represents a low degree of hazard when working with , or in close proximity to
ordance , ( or employees possibly adjacent to ) explosives and incendiary materials
which involves potential injury such as laceration of hands , face , or arms of the
employee engaged in the operation , irritation of the skin , minor burns and the
like ; minimal damage to immediate or adjacent work area or equipment being used .
All operations involving , unloading , storage , and hauling of ordance , explosive , and
incendiary ordnance material other than small arms ammunition . These differentials
are only applicable to work that has been specifically designated by the agency for
ordance , explosives , and incendiary material differential pay .
